    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-07-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-07-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="888"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d888">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.51 Public Works Debt/313</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Messersmith</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 137</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-02">July 2,
                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The receipt is acknowledged of your despatch no.
                    467 of June 24, 1940<note n="30" xml:id="d888fn1">Not printed.</note> with
                    regard to President Laredo Brú’s message to the Cuban Congress urging the
                    settlement of “the rest of the obligations originating in the public works
                    program”.</p>
                <p>You are authorized in your discretion to state to the appropriate officials of
                    the Cuban Government that the Department hopes that this matter will be settled
                    on the basis of the agreement reached between the Cuban Government and the
                    creditors in November 1938,<note n="31" xml:id="d888fn2">See <ref
                            target="frus1938v05#pg_472">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1938, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, pp. 472</ref> ff.</note> which agreement
                    was incorporated in a bill introduced into the Cuban Senate by Senator Casanova
                    in the same month. You will wish to stress the fact that the debt owed to the
                    firm of Purdy and Henderson was included in this settlement. It is the
                    Department’s view that the agreement in question now constitutes a clearly
                    recognized obligation of the Cuban Government to the creditors in question and
                    that <pb facs="0763" n="751" xml:id="pg_751"/> there would be no justification
                    for any further investigation or review of the claims.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sumner Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
